'''Carlton Osgood''' (1741-1816) was a [[cartographer]], land surveyor and mathematical teacher in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.il/books?id=7AE9XkG6G44C&pg=PT253&lpg=PT253&dq=Carlton+Osgood+cartographer&source=bl&ots=EjsltkiA_i&sig=5Rchgw2CtVkQAXb6Du5vFnSwRrs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi--vbh-JveAhXOZ1AKHRqYBP8Q6AEwC3oECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Carlton%20Osgood%20cartographer&f=false|title=On The Map: Why the world looks the way it does|last=Garfield|first=Simon|date=2012-10-04|publisher=Profile|isbn=9781847658555|language=en}}</ref> He was a key cartographer in the early mapping of [[Maine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oshermaps.org/exhibitions/printed-maps-of-maine-1793-1860/i-osgood-carlton-and-first-map-maine|title=I. Osgood Carlton and the First Map of Maine {{!}} Osher Map Library|website=www.oshermaps.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref> Carleton persuaded the Commonwealth to make a requirement that every town should make a detailed plan and he used these to create maps for Massachusetts and Maine. His maps in 1801 and 1802<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.davidrumsey.com/maps4992.html|title=Map Of Massachusetts. / Carleton, Osgood / 1801|website=www.davidrumsey.com|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref> offer information about economic activities in early Maine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oshermaps.org/exhibitions/printed-maps-of-maine-1793-1860/i-osgood-carlton-and-first-map-maine|title=I. Osgood Carlton and the First Map of Maine {{!}} Osher Map Library|website=www.oshermaps.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref>
