{{Islam}}
There are a number of uncertainties and '''disputed issues in the early''' [[history of Islam]].{{efn|[[Islam]] started with Muhammad. [[Muslim]]s believe that Islam did not start with him, but that it represents even previous [[Prophet]]s, such as [[Jesus in Islam|Jesus]], [[David in Islam|David]], [[Moses in Islam|Moses]], [[Abraham in Islam|Abraham]], [[Noah in Islam|Noah]] and [[Adam in Islam|Adam]].<ref name="Esposito1998">{{cite book |last=Esposito |first=John |title= Islam: The Straight Path (3rd ed.) |year=1998 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-511234-4 |pages=9, 12}}</ref><ref name="Esposito2002b">Esposito (2002b), pp. 4–5.</ref><ref name="Peters2003">{{cite book |last=Peters |first=F.E. |title=Islam: A Guide for Jews and Christians |year=2003 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=0-691-11553-2 |page=9}}</ref>}}

Most of these disputes can be traced to [[Shi'a]]-[[Sunni]] disagreements. Shi'a often argue that history has been distorted to further a [[Banu Umayyad]] agenda.<ref>Some 20th-century Shia scholars have protested the conversion of history into mythology. Prominent critics include: [[Morteza Motahhari]] ([http://al-islam.org/al-tawhid/ashura/ Meaning of 'Ashura: Misrepresentations & Distortions], [http://www.al-islam.org/al-tawhid/ashura/1.htm 'Ashura - History and Popular Legend] and [http://www.imamalinet.net/vigenam/moharam1422/en/e2.htm 'Ashura - Misrepresentations and Distortions] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051114091437/http://www.imamalinet.net/vigenam/moharam1422/en/e2.htm |date=November 14, 2005 }}), Abbas Qomi, author of ''Nafas al-Mahmoum'' ([http://www.al-islam.org/nafas/ Nafasul Mahmoom]), and Sayyid Abd-al-Razzaq Al-Muqarram, author of Maqtalul-Husayn ([http://www.bookrags.com/research/usayn-ibn-al-al--eorl-06/ Ḥusayn Ibn ʿAlī, Al, Encyclopedia of Religion])</ref> In many cases, complications with the [[historiography of early Islam]] have also resulted in lack of consensus within denominations of Islam.

==List of disputed issues==
The uncertainties include:
*The date of birth of [[Muhammad]]<ref name="OHoLA">The Oxford Handbook of Late Antiquity by Scott Fitzgerald Johnson 
(edited). "The historical Muhammad and the Qur'an".</ref>
*The date of Muhammad's death<ref name="OHoLA" />
*The age at which [[Khadija bint Khuwaylid|Khadija]] married Muhammad (25–40 years)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icraa.org/the-age-of-khadija-at-the-time-of-her-marriage-with-the-prophet/|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al-islam.org/articles/khadijah-daughter-khuwaylid-wife-prophet-muhammad-yasin-t-al-jibouri|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>
*The date of birth of [[Fatimah]] (±10 years)<ref>Fatima ['a] The Gracious http://www.al-islam.org/gracious/7.htm</ref><ref>There are differences of opinion on the exact date of her birth, but the widely accepted view is that she was born five years before the first [[Wahy|Quranic revelations]], during the time of the rebuilding of the [[Kaaba]] in 605, although this does imply she was over 18 at the time of her marriage, which was unusual in [[Arabian Peninsula|Arabia]].(See [http://encarta.msn.com/encnet/refpages/RefArticle.aspx?refid=761553645 MSN Encarta article on Fatimah] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070902023031/http://encarta.msn.com/encnet/refpages/RefArticle.aspx?refid=761553645 |date=2007-09-02 }} and [http://www.britannica.com/ebc/article-9364250/Fatimah Encyclopædia Britannica]) Twelver Shia sources, however, state that she was born either two or five years after the first [[Qur'an]]ic revelations, but that timeline would imply her mother was over fifty at the time of her birth.</ref>
*The marriage in which three of Khadija's three daughters were born<ref>For more, see [[Genealogy of Khadija's daughters]].</ref>
*The number of marriages Khadija was in before marrying Muhammad {{citation needed|date=November 2015}}
*The prohibition of [[Nikah Mut'ah]]{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}
*Date of birth of [[Aisha]]{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}
*Identity of the second wife of Muhammad ([[Sawda bint Zamʿa]] or Aisha){{citation needed|date=November 2015}}
*Disputes over the identity of the [[Umm Kulthum bint Ali|"Umm Khulthum" that married Umar]] (bint Ali, Bint Abu Bakr or a third){{citation needed|date=November 2015}}
*The existence of Fatimah's third son, [[Muhsin ibn Ali]]{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}
*The nomination of [[Ali Ibn Abi Talib]] as first [[caliph]] by Muhammad in [[Eid al-Ghadeer|Ghadir-e Khum]]<ref>Hadith of the pond of Khumm</ref> & [[Hadith of warning|Dawat ZulAsheera]]<ref>First invitation of Islam by Mohammad to his close relatives</ref>
*The ultimate faith of [[Abu Talib ibn Abd al-Muttalib]].
*Mohammad's inheritance and the dispute on the land of [[Fadak]] & [[Khaybar]]
*[[Burial place of Fatimah]]{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}
*The [[Satanic Verses]] incident

