{{About||the Nusach Sepharad|Nusach Sefard|Sephardim|Sephardi Jews}} '''Sepharad''' ({{Lang-he|סְפָרַד}} ''Sp̄āraḏ''; also ''Sefarad'', ''Sephared'', ''Sfard''), is a [[List of biblical names|biblical place name]] of uncertain location. It is mentioned only once in the [[Hebrew Bible|Bible]], in the [[Book of Obadiah]] ({{bibleverse||Obadiah|1:20|HE}}, 6th century BC). There are, however, [[Old Persian]] inscriptions that refer to two places called ''[[Saparda]]'' (alternative reading: ''Sparda''): one area in [[Media (region)|Media]] and another in [[Asia Minor]]. It is speculated that Sepharad could have been [[Sardis]], whose native [[Lydian language|Lydian]] name is ''Sfard'' or ''Sward''.<ref name="DusinberreDusinberre2003">On the Lydian name for Sardis, see {{cite book|author1=Elspeth R. M. Dusinberre|author2=Elspeth R. M.. Dusinberre|title=Aspects of Empire in Achaemenid Sardis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uWkzTBHB6ekC&pg=PA7|date=10 April 2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-81071-5|page=7}}</ref><ref name="Schapkow2015">{{cite book|author=Carsten Schapkow|title=Role Model and Countermodel: The Golden Age of Iberian Jewry and German Jewish Culture during the Era of Emancipation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=diLuCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA27|date=9 December 2015|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-1-4985-0803-2|page=27}}</ref>
Since the period of 2nd century [[Ancient Rome]], [[Spanish Jews]] gave the name "Sepharad" to the [[Iberian peninsula]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Remembering Sepharad: Jewish culture in medieval Spain |last=Torviso |first=Isidro Gonzalo Bango |year=2003 |publisher=State Corp. for Spanish Cultural Action Abroad |location=Washington National Cathedral |isbn=978-8496008274 |page=10 }}</ref> The descendants of [[Iberian Jews]] refer to themselves as [[Sephardi Jews]] (Hebrew, plural: ''Sephardim'') and identify [[Spain]] as "Sepharad" in [[Israeli Hebrew|modern Hebrew]].
==Version comparisons== * [http://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/16182/jewish/Chapter-1.htm Obadiah 1:20 (trans. Judaica Press)] "And this exiled host of the children of Israel who are [with] the Canaanites as far as Zarephath and the exile of Jerusalem which is in '''Sepharad''' shall inherit the cities of the southland" * [http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Bible/Obadiah1.html Obadiah 1:20 (NKJV)] "And the captivity of this host of the children of Israel, that are among the Canaanites, even unto Zarephath, and the captivity of Jerusalem, that is in '''Sepharad''', shall possess the cities of the South." * [http://bible.cc/obadiah/1-20.htm Obadiah 1:20 (Vulgate)] et transmigratio exercitus huius filiorum Israhel omnia Chananeorum usque ad Saraptham et transmigratio Hierusalem quae in '''Bosforo''' est possidebit civitates austri.
